POTENTIAL TALENTS¶

CONTEXT¶

The client is a talent sourcing and management company who are interested in finding talented individuals for sourcing these candidates to tech companies. They are facing three main challenges:

  • To understand what the role is very well to fill in a role, this requires understanding the tech company's requirements and what they are looking for in a potential candidate.
  • To understand what factors make a candidate shine for a given role that the tech company is searchinh for.
  • To find those paricularly talented individuals is another key challenge.

CURRENT SCENARIO¶

  • The nature of the taks required a lot of human labour and is fully of manual operations.
  • Presently, the client is semi-automated, sourcing is not a concern, but finding the right candidate is the main concern.
  • The client uses a keyword-based search method to find the right candidate for a given role, such as "Full-Stack Software Engineer" or "Aspiring Human Resources".

DATA DESCRIPTION¶

The data comes from the client's own sourcing efforts. Any field/attritbute that could directly reveal personal details have been removed and have been assigned a unique identifier for each candidate.

ATTRIBUTES¶

  • id : unique identifier for candidate (numeric)
  • job_title : job title for candidate (text)
  • location : geographical location for candidate (text)
  • connections: number of connections candidate has, 500+ means over 500 (text)

Output (desired target):

  • fit - how fit the candidate is for the role? (numeric, probability between 0-1)

Keywords: "Aspiring human resources" or "seeking human resources"

PROJECT GOALS¶

  • To predict how fit the candidate is based on the provided information (i.e. the target variable fit)
  • Build a ranking based robust system, in this case an unsupervised learning approach, to rank the fitting candidates based on a fitness which is our success metric.
  • Once an initial ranking is achieved, re-rank the candidates, because, for instance, the 1st candidate might not be the right fit, but the 7th might be.
  • Determine a cut-off point that would work for other roles without losing high potential candidates.
  • Automate the process in such a way that it prevents the human bias as much as possible.

"""
    plot_categorical_counts() : function to generate the count plots of discrete features
    @params : data - the pandas dataframe comprising the dataset, continuous_cols[] - an array holding the discrete features column names
    @return: None
"""

def plot_categorical_counts(data, categorical_cols):
    n = len(categorical_cols)
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5 * n))

    for i, col in enumerate(categorical_cols):
        plt.subplot(n, 1, i + 1)
        
        # Get top 10 most frequent categories
        top_categories = data[col].value_counts().nlargest(10).index
        filtered_data = data[data[col].isin(top_categories)]
        order = filtered_data[col].value_counts().index
        
        #ax = sns.countplot(data=filtered_data, x=col, order=order)
        ax = sns.countplot(data=filtered_data, x=col, order=order)
        
        total = len(filtered_data)
        for p in ax.patches:
            count = p.get_height()
            percent = f'{100 * count / total:.1f}%'
            ax.annotate(percent, 
                        (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., count), 
                        ha='center', va='bottom', fontsize=10)

        plt.title(f'Top 10 Count % of {col}')
        plt.xticks(rotation=45)
        plt.xlabel(col)
        plt.ylabel('Count')

    plt.tight_layout()

'''
parse_connections() : function that converts the connection columnn from string to number -> "500+" becomes int(500)
@params : val - the value in the connection column at an instance
@return : the converted integer values 
'''
def parse_connections(val):
    if pd.isna(val):
        return 0
    if isinstance(val, str) and "500" in val:
        return 500
    try:
        return int(val)
    except ValueError:
        return 0

# call the function and store in a new column - This will be later helpful during data preprocessing phase 
data["connections_numeric"] = data["connection"].apply(parse_connections)

# 1. Define and load NLP models
nlp = spacy.load("en_core_web_sm", disable=["ner", "parser"])
stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))
    
# 2. Create abbreviations map
abbreviation_map = {
        "hr": "human resources",
        "mgr": "manager",
        "sr": "senior",
        "jr": "junior",
        "engg": "engineering"
    }

'''
normalize_text() : function that normalize the values of column in three steps 
                    -> expands the abbrevations from the defined map
                    -> removed the stop words to make the values cleaner
                    -> lemmatizes the words so that it captures greater generalization during ranking
@params : text - the value in the defined column at an instance
@return : lemmatized tokens consolidated into a normalized string 
'''

# 3. Normalize the features for the ranking process
def normalize_text(text): 
    if pd.isna(text):
        return ""
    text = text.lower()
    text = re.sub(r'[' + string.punctuation + ']', ' ', text)
    words = text.split()
    # 1. Expand the abbreviations
    words = [abbreviation_map.get(w, w) for w in words]
    # 2. Remove stop words
    words = [w for w in words if w not in stop_words]
    # 4. Lemmatize the token for a generalized meaning
    doc = nlp(" ".join(words))
    lemmas = [token.lemma_ for token in doc]
    return " ".join(lemmas)


"""
preprocess_data() : function to apply text normalization and basic feature engineering to a dataframe.
                    -> Cleans and lemmatizes job_title
                    -> Standardizes location
                    -> performs sanity check on connections score as numeric 
@params : input datafarme
@return:  dataframe with preprocessing applied
"""
def preprocess_data(df):

    df = df.copy()
    df["job_title_clean"] = df["job_title"].apply(normalize_text)
    df["location_clean"] = df["location"].fillna("").str.lower().str.strip()
    
    # Optional: numeric conversion if not already done
    if "connections_numeric" not in df.columns:
        df["connections_numeric"] = df["connection"].replace("500+", 500).astype(int)

    return df

df_normalized = preprocess_data(df)

FEATURE ENGINEERING¶

COMPUTE FIT WITH COSINE SIMILARITY¶

In [16]:
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer
from sklearn.metrics.pairwise import cosine_similarity

"""
compute_cosine_fit() : function to compute cosine similarity between job titles and target phrases to calculate a fit score.
@params : -> df - input dataFrame with a 'job_title_clean' column
          -> target_phrases - list of target role phrases (e.g., ["aspiring human resources"])
          -> w_title, w_connections, w_location: preset weights for each component of the fit
@returns : output dataframe with calculated fit, computed job_vectors (i.e. feature vectors) and target vectors 
"""
def compute_cosine_fit(df, target_phrases, w_title=1.0, w_connections=0.0, w_location=0.0):

    df = df.copy()
    
    # Normalize target phrases
    target_phrases_norm = [normalize_text(p) for p in target_phrases]

    # Combine job titles + targets for vectorization
    corpus = df["job_title_clean"].tolist() + target_phrases_norm

    # Vectorize with TF-IDF
    vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer()
    tfidf_matrix = vectorizer.fit_transform(corpus)

    # Separate vectors
    job_vectors = tfidf_matrix[:len(df)]
    target_vectors = tfidf_matrix[len(df):]

    # Cosine similarity between jobs and targets
    similarities = cosine_similarity(job_vectors, target_vectors)
    df["title_similarity"] = similarities.mean(axis=1)

    # Normalize connection scores
    df["connections_score"] = df["connections_numeric"] / df["connections_numeric"].max()

    # Dummy location score
    df["location_score"] = 0.0

    # Weighted fit score
    df["fit"] = (
        w_title * df["title_similarity"] +
        w_connections * df["connections_score"] +
        w_location * df["location_score"]
    )

    return df, job_vectors, target_vectors  # return job_vectors, target_vectors to be reused for re-ranking step and KL computation

target_phrases = ["aspiring human resources", "seeking human resources"]
df_normalized, job_vectors, target_vectors = compute_cosine_fit(df_normalized, target_phrases)

df_normalized[["id", "job_title", "title_similarity", "connections_score", "location_score", "fit"]].sort_values("fit", ascending=False)

COMPUTE FIT KULLBACK-LIEBLER (KL) DIVERGENCE¶

In [17]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import normalize
from scipy.special import rel_entr
import numpy as np

"""
compute_kl_fit() : function to compute KL-divergence-based fit score for job titles compared to target vectors.

@params : df - input dataFrame to which the KL-based fit score will be added, 
          job_vectors - TF-IDF vectors of job titles
          target_vectors: TF-IDF vectors of target phrases

@returns : output dataframe with new calculate field 'fit_alt' (KL-based similarity score)
"""
def compute_kl_fit(df, job_vectors, target_vectors):

    df = df.copy()
    
    # 1. Convert sparse vectors to dense arrays
    job_vectors_array = job_vectors.toarray()
    target_vectors_array = target_vectors.toarray()

    # 2. L1 normalize to create valid probability distributions
    job_probs = normalize(job_vectors_array, norm='l1', axis=1)
    target_probs = normalize(target_vectors_array, norm='l1', axis=1)

    # 3. Add smoothing to avoid log(0)
    epsilon = 1e-10
    job_probs += epsilon
    target_probs += epsilon

    # 4. Compute average target distribution
    avg_target_prob = np.mean(target_probs, axis=0)

    # 5. KL divergence per job: KL(P || Q)
    kl_divs = [np.sum(rel_entr(p, avg_target_prob)) for p in job_probs]

    # 6. Inverse & normalize to convert to similarity
    kl_similarity = 1 / (1 + np.array(kl_divs))
    kl_similarity_norm = (kl_similarity - kl_similarity.min()) / (kl_similarity.max() - kl_similarity.min())

    # 7. Assign to dataframe
    df["fit_alt"] = kl_similarity_norm

    return df

df_normalized = compute_kl_fit(df_normalized, job_vectors, target_vectors)
df_normalized[["id", "job_title", "title_similarity", "connections_score", "fit", "fit_alt"]].sort_values("fit_alt", ascending=False)

OBSERVATIONS¶

SCATTER PLOT¶
  • There's a positive, nonlinear correlation b/w the two - as cosine similarity increases, KL similarity also increases.
  • Most data points are clustered toward the lower-left, i.e. many candidates have low similarity by both measures, likley the ones that are not HR-specific candidates.
  • A few points in the top-right quadrant show agreement b/w the two approaches for the high-fit candidates.
KDE PLOT¶
  • Cosine similarity (fit) has a sharper peak around 0.1–0.2 and drops off quickly.
  • KL Divergence similarity (fit_alt) has a wider, flatter distribution with a longer tail toward higher values.
INFERENCES AND SUGGESTED APPROACH¶
  • Both metrics generally agree on poor and strong matches, but diverge in the mid-range.
  • KL divergence tends to better distinguish the fit in high-similarity candidates, and captures behavior at greater granularity.
  • On the other hand, the Cosine similarity helps validate the matches based on token alignment as in the keyword match.
  • Suggest Approach - Use an integrated approach, use KL as primary signal and the Cosine similarity as second signal.

RANKING MODEL¶

BASELINE MODEL TESTING¶

In [19]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler

"""
integrate_fit_scores() : function to normalize and blend cosine and KL-based scores into a single integrated fit score. 

@params :
    - df: input dataFrame containing 'fit' (cosine) and 'fit_alt' (KL)
    - w_kl: weight for KL divergence
    - w_cosine: weight for cosine similarity

@return: df - output dataframe with calculated fields 'fit_norm', 'fit_alt_norm', 'fit_integrated'

"""

def integrate_fit_scores(df, w_kl=0.8, w_cosine=0.2):

    df = df.copy()

    scaler = MinMaxScaler()
    df["fit_norm"] = scaler.fit_transform(df[["fit"]])
    df["fit_alt_norm"] = scaler.fit_transform(df[["fit_alt"]])

    df["fit_integrated"] = (
        w_kl * df["fit_alt_norm"] + 
        w_cosine * df["fit_norm"]
    )

    return df

df_normalized = integrate_fit_scores(df_normalized, w_kl=0.8, w_cosine=0.2)

# Sort candidates by final fit

RE-RANK USING A STARRED CANDIDATE¶

In [24]:
import random

"""
re_rank_with_single_starred() : Re-ranks candidates by selecting one random candidate from top-N as a starred candidate.
@params :
    -> df - input dataFrame with 'fit_integrated' scores
    -> job_vectors - TF-IDF vectors of job titles
    -> top_n - Number of top candidates to sample from
    -> w_fit - Weight for original fit score
    -> w_starred - Weight for similarity to starred candidate
    
@return : df_re_ranked: output dataframe reranked based on updated fit score
"""

def re_rank_with_single_starred(df, job_vectors, top_n=10, w_fit=0.5, w_starred=0.5):

    df = df.copy()

    # Step 1–2: Randomly select one candidate from top-N
    df_top_n = df.sort_values("fit_integrated", ascending=False).head(top_n)
    random_selection = random.choice(df_top_n["id"].tolist())
    print(f"\n Randomly selected candidate ID (starred): {random_selection} \n")

    # Step 3: Mark the starred candidate
    df["is_starred"] = df["id"] == random_selection

    # Step 4: Get starred candidate vector
    starred_idx = df[df["id"] == random_selection].index[0]
    starred_vector = job_vectors[starred_idx]

    # Step 5: Cosine similarity to starred candidate
    df["similarity_to_starred"] = cosine_similarity(job_vectors, starred_vector).flatten()

    # Step 6: Combine fit scores
    df["fit_updated"] = (
        w_fit * df["fit_integrated"] +
        w_starred * df["similarity_to_starred"]
    )

    # Step 7: Re-rank
    df_re_ranked = df.sort_values("fit_updated", ascending=False)
    
    return df_re_ranked

df_re_ranked = re_rank_with_single_starred(df_normalized, job_vectors)

"""
get_potential_candidates() : function to filter out candidates above a specified quantile threshold based on fit score.

@params :
    -> df - input dataframe with fit scores
    -> score_col - Column name containing the final fit score
    -> quantile - Quantile to use as threshold (e.g., 0.75 for top 25%)

@return : potential_candidates - output dataframe filteredt with only top candidates
"""
def get_potential_candidates(df, score_col="fit_updated", quantile=0.75):
    df = df.copy()
    cutoff = df[score_col].quantile(quantile)
    selected_candidates = df[df[score_col] >= cutoff]
    print(f"\n Selected {len(selected_candidates)} candidates above threshold of {cutoff:.3f} (Quantile = {quantile})\n")
    return selected_candidates

MULTIPLE FEEDBACK SIMULATION¶

In [27]:
"""
re_rank_with_multiple_feedback_simulation() : function to simulate re-ranking based on multiple starred candidates from top-K fit scores.

@params : 
    -> df - DataFrame with 'fit_integrated'
    -> job_vectors - TF-IDF vectors for job titles
    -> N - Number of candidates to randomly star
    -> top_k - Number of top candidates to consider for random selection
    -> w_integrated - Weight for original integrated fit
    -> w_starred - Weight for similarity to starred candidates

@return : df_re_ranked_mfs - Re-ranked DataFrame after feedback-based update

"""

def re_rank_with_multiple_feedback_simulation(df, job_vectors, N=3, top_k=15, w_integrated=0.5, w_starred=0.5):

    df = df.copy()

    # Step 1: Randomly select N starred candidates from top-K
    df_top_n = df.sort_values("fit_integrated", ascending=False).head(top_k)
    starred_ids = random.sample(df_top_n["id"].tolist(), N)
    print(f"\n Randomly starred candidate IDs: {starred_ids} \n")

    # Step 2: Mark starred candidates
    df["is_starred"] = df["id"].isin(starred_ids)

    # Step 3: Get TF-IDF vectors for starred candidates
    starred_indices = df[df["is_starred"]].index
    starred_vectors = job_vectors[starred_indices]

    # Step 4–5: Compute average similarity to all starred candidates
    similarity_matrix = cosine_similarity(job_vectors, starred_vectors)
    df["similarity_to_starred"] = similarity_matrix.mean(axis=1)

    # Step 6: Recompute final score
    df["fit_updated"] = (
        w_integrated * df["fit_integrated"] +
        w_starred * df["similarity_to_starred"]
    )

    # Step 7: Sort by updated fit score
    df_re_ranked_mfs = df.sort_values("fit_updated", ascending=False)

    return df_re_ranked_mfs

df_re_ranked_mfs = re_rank_with_multiple_feedback_simulation(df_normalized, job_vectors)

BUSINESS RECOMMENDATIONS¶

AUTOMATED I/O PIPELINE¶

The ranking algorithm can be robustly automated using the following pipeline, since the entire methodology has been made functional:

INPUT : The client/user is required to only set three inputs:

  • The CSV/JSON file in this consistent format - id, job_title, location, connection - [*Must be ensured by the client]
  • Set target keywords, such as "Aspiring Human Resources", "Seeking Human Resources" - It can be updated as per requirement
  • How many candidates to star? Can star only 1 or even multiple candidates

OUTPUT : The client will recieve a list of potential candidates based on the ranking algorithm inbuilt with dedicated functions.

FUTURE SCALABILITY¶

  • The pipeline can be easily extended to other job roles by modifying the target keywords.
  • The feedback mechanism and thresholding approach are role-agnostic, making the system scalable across departments.
  • Since the algorithm is fully functional, it can be integrated into HR dashboards or web-based ATS systems for real-time candidate shortlisting.
